Chinese scientists are warning that the country's northeast breadbasket regions are in danger of losing their fertility because of soil erosion and degeneration.
Sand storms in northwest China's Gansu Province are reducing sections of Great Wall to mounds of dirt and may cause them to disappear in about 20 years, archaeological experts say.
An afforestation project has begun to curb desertification and soil erosion in southwest China's Tibet Autonomous Region.
China's desertification acreage had shrunk by 37,900 square kilometers from 2000 to 2004, said a senior official with the State Forestry Administration (SFA) on Thursday.
A three-year investigation reveals almost 40 percent of China's territory, or 3,569,200 square kilometers of land,suffers from soil erosion.
